  "local_port": 43226,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How was the International Space Station built?",
  "response": "The International Space Station (ISS) is one of the most complex and ambitious construction projects ever undertaken in space. Its construction involved multiple international space agencies, including NASA, Roscosmos, the European Space Agency (ESA), the Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency (JAXA), and the Canadian Space Agency (CSA). Here's an overview of how the ISS was built:\n\n1. **Planning and International Collaboration:**\n   - Planning for the ISS began in the 1980s, with the aim of creating a permanently inhabited orbiting research facility that could serve as a platform for scientific research and international cooperation.\n   - The project brought together various space agencies from around the world, each contributing specific modules, resources, and technology.\n\n2. **Launch and Assembly in Orbit:**\n   - The ISS was assembled piece by piece in space, with different components launched aboard space shuttles, Russian Proton rockets, and Soyuz rockets.\n   - The first module, Zarya (\"Sunrise\" in Russian), was launched by a Russian Proton rocket in November 1998.\n   - Over the years, numerous modules and components were added. These include the U.S. Unity module, the Russian Zvezda service module, and others like Destiny (U.S. lab), Kibo (Japanese lab), and Columbus (ESA lab).\n\n3. **Construction by Astronauts and Cosmonauts:**\n   - Astronauts and cosmonauts aboard the ISS conducted dozens of spacewalks to connect various components, route cables, and perform maintenance. The Canadian-built Canadarm2 robotic arm played a vital role in maneuvering parts and assisting with assembly.\n\n4. **Addition of Solar Panels and Other Systems:**\n   - Large solar arrays were installed to provide power to the station. These panels were also delivered in segments and deployed in orbit.\n   - Systems for life support, water filtration, power distribution, and communications were gradually integrated into the station\u2019s operation.\n\n5. **Completion and Continuous Upgrades:**\n   - The ISS has been continuously inhabited since November 2000.\n   - While the main assembly was largely completed in the early 2010s, the station still receives upgrades and new modules. For instance, in 2021, Russia added the Nauka multipurpose laboratory module, and other nations continue to develop and plan contributions.\n\n6. **Logistics and Resupply Missions:**\n   - Resupply missions, using various spacecraft like the Dragon by SpaceX, Cygnus by Northrop Grumman, and the Russian Progress capsules, deliver essential supplies, equipment, and experiments to support the crew aboard the ISS.\n\nThe ISS was not built by any single nation, but through an unprecedented level of international collaboration in engineering, science, and diplomacy. The station serves as a testament to what can be achieved when various countries come together with a shared vision for exploration and discovery.",
